<h3 id="si-prefixes">SI Prefixes</h3>
<p>One of the advantage of using the SI Units is instead of giving other names to units of very large or very small quantities, prefixes can be used. For example, a 25,000 m road can also be presented as 25 km, using the (k) symbol for “<em>kilo</em>,” multiplying the value to 1,000 or $10^3$. Another example would be a single grain of rice with a mass of approximately 29 mg, which can also be interpreted as $29\times 10^{-3}$g or 0.029 g. Table 3 indicates some of the prefixes used to denote multiples of ten.</p>

